  "bib_entries": {
    "117202155": {
      "title": "Frequency domain visual processing",
      "abstract": "The sensitivity of human spatial vision has traditionally been characterised either by the minimum size of a high-contrast test figure which allows an observer to detect or recognize it, or by the minimum visible luminance difference between a large sharp-bordered target and the uniform background on which it appears. Information of this kind is not, however, adequate for determining what quality of reproduction of images is necessary for satisfactory human viewing, an important question to designers of, for example, photographic or television systems. Thus it is not surprising to find that a more powerful technique for characterising human visual sensitivity was initially introduced because of its potential application in these areas."
    }
  },
